@node WBSTART "Starting Abuse from Workbench"

To run Abuse from Workbench, double click on the Starter icon. A small
window will pop up. You can configure Abuse form here. You can give
Starter a settings file as an icon tooltype, INIFILE. The default is
Abuse.ini. You can also use Starter as default tool in project icons.
The main archive contains examples for this. There are two other TOOLTYPES:
ABUSE=<name> gives an alternate name for the Abuse executable. The other
CONSOLE=<window description> describes the console window to use for
output. See the AmigaDOS documentation (Hint: something like CON:0/0/... :)

Here are the options settable form Starter:

@{i}General@{ui}:

    @{b}Game Mode:@{ub} This sets the game mode to either game (for normal
        play) or edit (for editing levels).
        (Default: Game)

    @{b}FPS Limiter:@{ub} This enables or disables the FPS limiter. Normally,
        the framerate will be limited to 15 fps, to avoid drastic changes. If
        you do not want to limit, set this to off. You may also try this for
        slow machines that do not get too high, anyway.
        (Default: on)

    @{b}Light F/X:@{ub} This disables the real-time light. If your machine is
        too slow, this will be done automatically. You may also switch the light
        on and off by pressing F6 during play. Note: this option can have
        great impact on speed. For example, my A4000/060 does 22 fps with light
        enabled (no limiter, off course), and 35 without light.
        (Default: on)

    @{b}Temp dir:@{ub} This gadget holds the name of the directory that holds the
        @{i}fastload.dat@{ui} file. This file may be large, sometimes 1 - 2 MB.
        If you are low on memory, you can point this to a disk-based directory.
        (Default: t:)

    @{b}Startup file:@{ub} Here, you can give the name of a lisp file that will
        be executed instead of abuse.lsp. This option is more or less obsolete,
        as addon modules are the new way for this. This option corresponds to the
        -lsf option.
        (Default: none)

    @{b}Addon module:@{ub} This is the name of an addon module. An example of an
        addon is the deathmat Deathmatch module. This option corresponds to the
        -a option.
        (Default: none)

    @{b}Additional options:@{ub} This field is appended to the command line on
        execution of the Abuse binary. You can give additional options not covered
        by Starter.
        (Default: empty)

@{i}Audio@{ui}:

    @{b}Sound enabled:@{ub} Setting this to off completely disables sound.
        AHI isn`t even opened.
        (Default: on)

    @{b}AHI Mode:@{ub} You can give the numerical AHI mode number here, or
        leave it unchanged at -1 to let AHI use it`s default audio mode.
        (Default: -1)

    @{b}Mixing Frequency:@{ub} Use this to set the mixing frequency. Sound is
        normally onl 11025 KHz in Abuse, so you may set this accordingly, or
        leave it at -1 for default.
        (Default: -1)

    @{b}Select:@{ub} Click here to select an AHI audio mode. A standard AHI
        requester will pop up. Refer to the AHI docs for more information.

    @{b}Channels:@{ub} The number of channels to use. The more channels, the
        more sounds can be played simultaneously.
        (Default: 8)

    @{b}Boost:@{ub} Volume boost. The more channels, the softer the sound. Use
        this to compensate this.
        (Default: 2)

@{i}Video@{ui}:

    @{b}Driver:@{ub} Select the video system to use: RTGMaster, CGX/P96, AGA, ECS.
        (Default: RTGMaster)

    @{b}Pixel doubling:@{ub} Doubles pixels in game, thus accelerating light
        calculation. Note however that the resolution must be at least 640x400
        for this option to work. Corresponding to the -2 command line option.
        (Default: off)

    @{b}Double buffering:@{ub} Enable double buffering. This options can only be used
        with the RTGMaster (not on Workbench).
        (Default: off)

    @{b}WB Color Change:@{ub} Allow RTGMaster to change the screens colors when
        running on Workbench. If you experience strange colors when running in
        a Workbench window, try this.
        (Default: off)

    @{b}CV64 compatible:@{ub} Set this if you have a CV64 (not 3D).
        (Default: off)

    @{b}Video Mode:@{ub} Select best mode, or open a requester (CGX/Native)
        (Default: Best mode)

    @{b}Direct access:@{ub} Access display memory directly (CGX only). Note that
        this can either slow down, or accelerate Abuse. As a rule of thump,
        if you have a slow graphics board, leave it off.
        (Default: off)

    @{b}Width/Height:@{ub} Dimensions of the display to use. This is ignored
        when using a mode requester.
        (Default: 320x200)

@{i}Net@{ui}:

    @{b}Game Mode:@{ub} Enable or disable network support. Remote means network
        enabled, local means disabled. Local corresponds to the -nonet option.
        Note that if you want to start a net game from the main menu, you
        have to use Remote.
        (Default: Remote)

    @{b}Server name:@{ub} Name of a server hosting a net game. This corresponds to
        the option -net <server name>. When using this option, Abuse will directly
        connect to the server, or quit if it can`t contact it.
        (Default: none)


@endnode
