@node FAQ "The Abuse FAQ"
(Note: As this is the first release, there is not much to say in this section. More may come in the future.)

@{b}About these weird effects in the ECS version...@{ub}
Yes, I can see it too, there was nothing unusual in your last cigarette. The ECS version has a problem with the C2P stuff. It may be fixed later...

@{b}How do I report a bug in Abuse ?@{ub}
Have a look at the @{"Disclaimer" link LEGAL} section for our email addresses.

@{b}Where do I get the files needed to play ? @{ub}
Instructions on how to get the required files are available @{"here" link OBTAIN}. If you`ve got them, look @{"here" link INSTALL} for installation instructions.

@{b}Is there any place where I can download the registered files ? Any Warez/Pirate sites ? @{ub}
(Yes, this IS frequently asked). We will not send pirated files, so don`t even bother to ask. And, we do not know where to get a pirated copy. Period.

@{b}Why is there both RtgMaster and CyberGfx/AGA in it ?@{ub}
The EGCS compiler used to compile Abuse has some problems with RtgMaster. This will be fixed later. We suggest you use RtgMaster, as it supports double buffering and custom C2P code. Aditionally, it supports playing in a Workbench window, which isn`t possible on CyberGfx due to a bug in the library.

@{b}Abuse crashes as soon as I start it (after a reboot)@{ub}
This is a bug caused by the opening of rtgmaster.library from egcs. Will be fixed soon.

@{b}Abuse tells me something about "write permission" to /tmp... @{ub}
Yup, Abuse wanted to write to /tmp, not tmp: . This is no problem with
ixprefs "Translate /" option enabled, but this isn`t the default behavior.
It`s fixed in the 1.1 release

@{b}Abuse is too slow, what can I do ?@{ub}
Abuse was originally aimed at a 486/DX2 and early Pentium processors. Thus, it`s a
bit slow on older machines. One of the time consuming things is the light. You can
switch it off with the F6 key. Mat Colton pointed out that you can also limit the
amount of processor time for sound in AHI prefs.

@{b}Talking about sound, when using my sound card, Abuse gets really jerky.@{ub}
Yes, that`s something some folk observed. We know this, and it will be fixed later.

@endnode
@node PLAY "Playing Abuse"

This page lists the Amiga specific changes. For more general information, refer to the README, included in the @{b}abuse200.zip@{ub} archive.

The Keyboard layout has been changed to match the Amiga keyboard. Running and jumping is done with the cursor keys, while cursor down activates lifts and teleporters.

The Del and Help keys switch weapons. Note that this is different from the PC version, which used CTRL and INS. The number keys on the top row may also be used to select the weapon. Additionally, F6 toggles lightning effects. Note, though, that lighting is also atumatically disablede whenever the frame rate drops too low.

Speaking of the frame rate, it is automatically limited to 15 fps to keep speed constant. To turn off this limiter, press F7. Finally, to get a guess at the frame rate, press F8 to show it in the top left corner. The number on the top is the frame rate ×10, while the next three numbers are some debug info.

@endnode
@node INTRO "Introduction"

Welcome to Abuse Amiga...

  If you still remember Obliterator from Psygnosis, you're very close to what Abuse looks like. But under the hood, there's @{b}much@{ub} more...

  Basically, Abuse is a Jump-and-run game for the high-level machine. This means that the requirements to run Abuse are a bit higher than usual for a game of that type, but that's mostly due to the amount of special effects the game features.

  Plus, Abuse is almost ridiculously extendible. Since almost the entire game workings are programmed in Common Lisp (with a few additional functions), it is very easy to add new objects, new aliens, and basically everything you can think of. With the Abuse engine, it is quite possible to "re-build" such games as @{i}Another World@{ui} or @{i}Flashback@{ui} as well as things like @{i}Turrican@{ui}. All you need is a bit of graphics and programming skills.

A word about the graphics systems.

  Abuse uses as it`s primary graphics system the rtgmaster system, written by Steffen Haueser. As a secondary option, it also supports CyberGraphX and AGA native. These options are only to compensate for difficulties with the egcs-compiler used for Abuse. RtgMaster gives you double buffering, customizable C2P and Workbench window support. However, if you run into trouble with it, try -aga/-cgx. These problems will be fixed later.

Features include:
  - @{b}Dynamic light effects@{ub}. Every level is lightsourced in realtime, allowing such nice
    effects like explosions and gunfire.
  - @{b}Network play@{ub}. Up to 8 players via TCP/IP in Deathmatch Mode.
  - @{b}Level Editor@{ub}. Build your own levels, fill them with monsters, then blast them to
    pieces.

And, new for the Amiga version:
  - @{b}Network code actually works@{ub}. The original version had a bug that, when using media
    with small MTU, trashed files that where trasnfered.
  - @{b}Stereo sound@{ub}. The original had only mono.

@endnode
